This April in Monte-Carlo, Musetti rose to the occasion in his first ATP Masters 1000 final to claim a 6-3 opening set against Alcaraz. But he won just one game after that, hampered by a right-leg injury. One month later in the Rome semi-finals, Alcaraz played a pragmatic match in windy conditions to knock out the home favourite, showing composure and grit to earn a 6-3, 7-6(4) victory. He went on to win the title by beating Jannik Sinner in the trophy round.

Watch Alcaraz-Musetti Rome highlights:

An Alcaraz-Sinner rematch could await in the Roland Garros final, but Musetti will have his shot to dethrone the champ first. Any upset bid will start with protecting his serve, a shot Musetti has improved this season after some offseason tweaking.

""We shortened a bit the motion to have more control, and then I got more confidence in what I was having as a motion,"" he said, noting previous struggles with consistency and his toss. ""Right now I think in really many difficult situations, I make an ace or have my serve as a weapon, and it was a pretty big change also for my game.""



Musetti's overall game earned praise from Alexander Zverev this week, with the German commenting on the ""very stable"" tennis he has found during the clay-court season. Can the Italian build on that solid foundation and take his game to new heights?

Less than two months after he reached his first ATP Masters 1000 final, he is one victory away from his first Grand Slam title match. But Alcaraz, one year younger at 22, is already a seven-time Masters 1000 champ and four-time major titlist.

The 23-year-old Musetti has earned his place among the game's elite with his breakthrough season. Now he has a chance to prove he can beat the very best on the biggest stage.

 

