"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=Supernatural","10 Weirdest Details in Supernatural That Don't Add Up","https://www.cbr.com/supernatural-weirdest-details-about-series/","Thu, 05 Jun 2025 02:00:00 GMT","

The CW's Supernatural is one of the most beloved franchises of the last two decades, but with various complex story arcs, character resurrections and shifting plot devices, it's easy to see how things can get a bit muddy at times. Villains come and go, some having much more impact than others. Certain relics work on specific creatures while losing their potency. When time travel and multiple dimensions were introduced, the series' storylines became shaky.

Sam and Dean themselves have both died and returned several times over. While Supernatural was initially supposed to end after 5 seasons, the fan response urged the studio and show creators to keep the Winchesters around for much longer than intended. This welcome but elongated stay has led to a few head-scratching details in the show's history.

In Season 5 of Supernatural, viewers are introduced to the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse. Each of the four wears rings that help them manifest in human form. The rings themselves are also the keys to unlocking Lucifer's cage and starting the apocalypse. While Death stands out as much older and somewhat immune to the rules that govern the other three, they each represent an aspect of human nature that is necessary to ignite the end of times.

Horseman

Actor

First Appearance

Death

Julian Richings

Season 5, Episode 21, ""Two Minutes to Midnight""

War

Titus Welliver

Season 5, Episode 2, ""Good God, Y'ALL""

Pestilence

Matt Frewer

Season 5, Episode 19, ""Hammer of the Gods""

Famine

James Otis

Season 5, Episode 14, ""My Bloody Valentine""

In the macabre world of The CW's Supernatural, the Winchester brothers have faced some of the most vile and powerful villains in TV history.

Since Death existed just as long as life itself, viewers might concede that his arc stands alone and separate from his brothers. However, when Death is killed in a later season, he must be replaced by a reaper as the role of Death is necessary to the universe itself. When the other horsemen are defeated by Sam and Dean, their roles are never replaced. The horsemen were crucial to the plot of Season 5, widely considered the best season of Supernatural, and ultimately fizzled out as major villains in a single episode.

In season 8 of Supernatural, viewers are introduced to the history of the Men of Letters. The Men of Letters were a secret, occult organization that had long monitored the history of magic and monsters, gathering data and means by which humanity could survive and defend themselves against things that go bump in the night. They would work with hunters by supplying information or materials necessary to aid them in their struggles.

Initially, it seems the Men of Letters are extinct until it is revealed there is an entire sect of the organization still very active in Britain. They possess ample resources and are highly organized, as seen when they provide the Winchesters with the hyperbolic pulse generator device, which they use to defeat Lucifer again. When conflict arises between the Winchesters and the British Men of Letters, their entire base of operation is overthrown, and their footing in America is severed through the attack on a single base. For a secret organization with decades of experience and resources, this defeat seems sudden and unrealized.

Season 7 is considered a bit of a bumpy stretch of road in the Supernatural ride. One highlight of the season, however, was the introduction of fan-favorite character Kevin Tran. Kevin was a smart young kid, focused solely on his studies before he was chosen as the next prophet of the lord. He is watched over by the angels as he learns to decipher the tablets until he is ultimately kidnapped by the Leviathans. The Leviathans wanted Kevin to read their tablet before Crowley interfered with his demons and took Kevin. He's thrown into the world with all the forces of good and evil clamoring for his services.

Supernatural, as a series, was filled with highs and lows. But certain choices left fans of one season deeply divided even after the show's end.

Kevin spends most his on-screen time in Supernatural under duress. Even though he was thrust into this position at no fault of his own, he assisted Sam and Dean to the best of his capabilities. For a large portion of season 8, Kevin is decoding the demon tablet for the Winchesters as Sam is undertaking the trials to shut the gates of Hell forever. In the 9th episode of Season 9, under orders from Metatron, the angel Galadreel assassinates Kevin, smiting him in the Men of Letters bunker. This death was sudden and never fully foreshadowed. It doesn't help that Sam and Dean barely mention Kevin past this point.

In the finale of season 8, viewers witness all the angels fall from heaven at the hands of Metatron's spell. Throughout season 8, Metatron tricks Castiel into aiding him in the completion of what Castiel thinks are the angel trials to lock the gates of Heaven. Metatron is lying to Castiel and using the items collected by Castiel to cast a spell that will expel all angels from Heaven. This leads to the primary storyline of Season 9 focusing on the angels adjusting to life on Earth and forming various warring factions hoping to reenter Heaven. The result is a jumbled mess of follow-the-leader that seems to shift each week.

The leaders of the main primary factions are angels named Bartholomew and Malachi. Bartholomew is billed as a fearsome warrior angel, once under the command of Castiel during the war that took place after the first apocalypse. Malachi, known as the Anarchist Angel, is more brutal in his approach and spreads this trait among his followers. However, Bartholomew is easily dispatched by Castiel after nearly a full season of buildup, when they meet to discuss Castiel's recruitment to Bartholomew's side. Malachi's fate is even more underwhelming as he is killed by the angel Galadreel off-screen. The Angel Civil War and its leaders were ultimately just a season full of filler and storylines that led to a dead end.

 The Leviathans were God's first pet project in Supernatural. Before man, before angels, Chuck created the ancient Leviathans, which proved to be a big mistake. Also known as the Old Ones, the Leviathans were a perfect killing machine, devouring everything in sight. God was forced to create the realm of Purgatory to house the Old Ones to prevent them from destroying all of his creations. So, when Castiel accidentally unleashes the primordial beings at the end of Season 6 by opening a portal to Purgatory and absorbing all the souls within, viewers were expecting a lot of carnage from the Leviathans.

Initially, the Leviathans appear unstoppable. Even decapitation only slows them down, as their heads eventually reattach. As they are older than angels, even angels fear them and resort to flight before attempting to fight. The oldest of the monsters seems to be no match for the Leviathan either, as seen when the Alpha Vampire must succumb to their orders. So, when it was revealed that the ultimate answer to battling the Old Ones is borax, fans found it extremely underwhelming, to say the least. Sheriff Jody Mills unintentionally discovers this weakness when cleaning Bobby's house, and the borax, found in most cleaning products, drips onto their Leviathan captive.

In the early years of Supernatural, demons were a big deal. The primary story arc that launched the show focused on the demon Azazel and his murder of Mary Winchester. The first two seasons are dedicated to the Winchesters searching for their father and hunting Azazel to avenge their mother. In the season finale of the second season, many of Hell's inhabitants are released when the Devil's Gate is opened. The episode marks a major turning point in the series where demons become one of the primary antagonists. Outside of exorcism, the only way the Winchesters have to kill demons is the use of the demon-killing knife, which they retrieve from the demon Ruby.

When the seven deadly sins are released in the first episode of Season 3, it's labeled as one of the biggest challenges modern hunters have ever faced. The seven sins have been imprisoned in Hell since the Dark Ages, and when they're discovered on Earth, Bobby is visibly shaken. Crossroads demons were also much more prominent in the early seasons, seen as a major issue for Sam and Dean as they often tricked humans into trading their souls for wishes, which would ultimately backfire. As Supernatural progresses, the demons become weaker and commonplace and are easily dispatched. Later, demons in Supernatural fit more into the monster-of-the-week category, more so than the season-long antagonist that appeared during the first years of the show.

When Sam and Dean go to Heaven in Season 5 of Supernatural, they encounter the angel Joshua in Heaven's garden. Initially, the Winchesters are being followed and attacked by the angel Zachariah until Joshua intervenes, telling Zachariah that he needs to speak with them because God has a message for them. It's hinted that God sometimes speaks to Zachariah because they both consider themselves gardeners. Sam and Dean tell Joshua they wish to speak with God about the upcoming apocalypse on Earth in hopes of having God intervene and save humanity. While part of what Joshua tells them is true, it is not the whole story.

Though Supernatural didn't reveal Chuck Shurley's identity as God until Season 11, hints about his true nature started popping up in Season 4.

Joshua is right when he tells Sam and Dean that God has intervened by saving them up to this point. For one, he transports them to the airplane when Lucifer's cage is opened. He also brought Castiel back to life to aid them. Joshua says this is the most God has done for anyone in quite some time, which is partly true. However, viewers know in retrospect that God, under the guise of Chuck, was much more involved than Joshua revealed. He was writing the story as it unfolded throughout all of season 5. Chuck is well aware of all the events taking place and points Sam and Dean in the right direction all over the apocalypse-filled season.

In season 8 of Supernatural, Sam undertakes the Trials of God. As the prophet Kevin Tran reveals to the Winchesters via his translation of the demon tablet, the trials are tasks designed by God for one to undertake should they wish to close the gates of Hell forever. Most of the season highlights Sam's journey as he completes the trials and the negative effects that the trials have on him. Sam has been visibly ill since the completion of the first trial. When pursuing Metatron, Sam collapses from a fever of 107, forcing Dean to throw him in a tub full of ice to save his life.

Trial

Episode

Air Date

Kill a hellhound and bathe in its blood

Trial and Error

February 13, 2013

Rescue an innocent soul from Hell

Taxi Driver

April 3, 2013

Cure a demon

Sacrifice

May 15, 2013

After the Winchesters save Bobby's soul from Hell, the only trial that remains is to cure a demon. Sam and Dean ultimately capture Crowley and lock him in a church, and begin curing him. While Sam continues with the efforts to cure Crowley, Dean encounters Naomi and informs him that if Sam finishes the trials, he will die. Castiel teleports Dean to Sam, and Dean tells Sam that if he doesn't stop, it will lead to his death. After much convincing, Sam agrees to stop as he and Dean witness the angels falling from Heaven. The effects of the trial and the storyline all but disappear from this point forward, rendering the main arc of season 8 all but useless in the grand scheme of Supernatural.

Jack Kline is the offspring of Lucifer and the human Kelly Kline, making him a powerful Nephilim. Jack's powers are expressed before his birth when he chooses Castiel as his guardian and aids Castiel in dispatching the demon Dagon while still in his mother's womb. Thinking that because Jack is the child of Lucifer, he will be pure evil, Kelly attempts to destroy herself and Jake, but Jake resurrects Kelly to save her and himself. However, it is after Jack is born that viewers are introduced to the scope of his true power.

Jack appears to be just like any child after he is born until the Winchesters realize he is growing up at a rapid pace. In a matter of days, Jack is a young man. The reason for his rapid growth is never explained, nor is the reason for it stopping ever addressed. Despite his apparent age, Jack still has the mind of a young child and has to learn his abilities from scratch. If he were aging at such a pace from the moment he was born, it would make sense that he is much older after being alive for a few weeks.

Throughout the history of Supernatural, Sam and Dean have had to find creative ways to gather intel on the various cases they've undertaken during their hunting careers. From hacking into sensitive and encrypted computer systems and posing as police officers, the Winchesters have done it all for the sake of solving the case. Not to mention the endless credit card scams to eat and buy hotel rooms. Hunting monsters doesn't pay well, after all. The boys keep drawers filled with throwaway phones and forged badges to use at the drop of a hat, should a clue come back from some far-off agency.

It can be hard for viewers to swallow, however, that in the 15 seasons of Supernatural, the Winchesters have rarely, if ever, been apprehended for illegal activities. One would think that with the resources the FBI has, at least one or two agents would find it odd that the same two individuals show up at the scenes of many violent, high-profile cases. Not to mention, the Winchesters usually have fun with their agent names, typically using the last names of famous musicians. Considering the cultural popularity of many of the musicians' names used, it would make sense for them to be discovered as frauds a few times.

